post_text:
August 19, 2020

To the Entire Black Knight Learning Community,

At the Marion Board of Education meeting on August 17, 2020, the board voted to alter our school calendar. The Superintendent’s Conference Day on March 12th, 2021 is now a student attendance day, and the first day of school for students’ attendance this fall was moved from September 8th to September 9th. Part of the reason for this change was to align our calendar with that of the recently changed WF-L BOCES calendar. A more significant reason for this change was to have an additional conference day with our staff at the beginning of the year to complete the training and protocol reviews for all of the health and safety mitigation requirements related to the COVID-19 virus.

We apologize for any inconveniences this might have caused for your families.

Respectfully,

Don Bavis

GREAT NEWS! Free meals will continue for all Marion area children 18 and younger. Meals will be available on Mondays and Wednesdays, through August 19, for pick up at the gym door behind the Marion Elementary School. post_text: This musical was one of the highlights of the school year! We are so fortunate to have such talented students!
shared_text:
Marion Musical
May 2 at 5:37 AM ·

AMAZING JOB TO EVERYONE INVOLVED IN THE PRODUCTION OF BEAUTY AND THE BEAST! Just received these comments from Elenbe judges. A virtual awards show may be coming at the end of the month.

ELENBE 2019-20 Judges' Comments for Marion, "The Beauty and The Beast"

Very Impressive! Felt like I was watching a "Broadway Musical".
Your production was over the top! Everything was like a Broadway production!
Excellent entertaining program. Well done!
A perfect choice for Marion; A real feast for the eyes. Every little princess in the audience was enthralled (I sat behind one and watched her react). I expected Marion to wow me with "Be Our Guest" and was not disappointed - it was eyepopping!
Overall good show. You do a very good job with such a large cast. Most in big costumes did a great job of moving and facial expressions.
Good show. Some delay in between songs. There were some missed lines, but a lot of lines to remember. Mrs. Potts did a great job. Everyone moved and danced well with the elaborate costumes. great job.

KUDOS TO THE BEST CAST, CREW, and STAFF ever!

post_text:
To Our Marion Black Knight Family,

Following Governor Cuomo’s executive order that all non-essential employees “stay home”, we have reviewed our COVID-19 food delivery procedures. Although their role in creating and delivering meals to our students make them as “essential” as ever, we feel we can further minimize their risks of exposure to the virus through some modifications of our plans.

Beginning on Wednesday, March 25th, meals will be available for pickup at the Marion Elementary School from 11 AM until 12:30 PM on Mondays and Wednesdays only. Two days worth of meals will be picked up on Monday, and three days worth on Wednesday. Until the new procedures go into effect on March 25th, daily delivery will continue on March 23rd and March 24th. By dividing our food service staff into two teams, each preparing and delivering food only once a week, we limit their potential exposure to one time a week.

Finally, we would like to personally commend our food service staff for their commitment and dedication to our Marion students.
text:
To Our Marion Black Knight Family,

Following Governor Cuomo’s executive order that all non-essential employees “stay home”, we have reviewed our COVID-19 food delivery procedures. Although their role in creating and delivering meals to our students make them as “essential” as ever, we feel we can further minimize their risks of exposure to the virus through some modifications of our plans.

Beginning on Wednesday, March 25th, meals will be available for pickup at the Marion Elementary School from 11 AM until 12:30 PM on Mondays and Wednesdays only. Two days worth of meals will be picked up on Monday, and three days worth on Wednesday. Until the new procedures go into effect on March 25th, daily delivery will continue on March 23rd and March 24th. By dividing our food service staff into two teams, each preparing and delivering food only once a week, we limit their potential exposure to one time a week.

Finally, we would like to personally commend our food service staff for their commitment and dedication to our Marion students.

As part of the required COVID-19 Closure Plan, the district is required to assist essential health care workers and first responders in finding childcare while school is not in session. The district has two licensed daycare providers, both of whom have availability – All My Children Daycare and First Steps Daycare. In addition, you may find other providers and resources at childcarecouncil.com. If you are an essential health care worker and/or a first responder and are in need of additional assistance finding childcare please contact the district and we will do our best to assist you.

If you need contact information for the daycare providers above or additional assistance, please contact bschoonerman@marioncs.org

Musical tickets will be sold for all 4 shows Sunday, March 1 in the Auditorium Lobby from 11am to 1 pm and again from 3pm to 5pm. Tickets for Sunday March 8th are stand alone tickets and can not be exchanged with tickets from the first 3 shows. It will still be reserved seating and $8 per ticket.

There will also be ticket sales at the elementary school on Monday from 2:45 - 3:30pm and Wednesday from 2:00 - 4:00. Please friends not to park out front of the elementary school due to busses at dismissal, please use the municipal lot next to the school. Ticket sales will also continue as normal Monday thru Friday in the high school lobby from 7:30am - 1:00pm.

shared_text:
MES FARM CLUB
October 24, 2019 at 10:40 PM ·

Welcome back FARM CLUB! Boy did we start with a 💥!
Over 50 kids!
Double what we had last year!!!

We had the kids work together to get in order based on birthdays from Jan- Dec. thats how they were split up into groups. They were able to work with kids they might not work with everyday. Then onto building...toothpick pyramid stem challenge. The kids had clay and 40 toothpicks and had to make the tallest tower that was considered a pyramid. They had to work together. A successful meeting:)

Marion Central School District
September 27, 2019 at 7:13 PM ·

📢Marion is in search of individuals passionate about creating a positive, supportive and respectful learning culture for students!
.
.
In order to create an Alliance for a Kinder Culture, the school district is creating a team of faculty, staff, students, parents, administration and all other interested stakeholders to spearhead this important movement. It is our belief that coming together and accepting this challenge as a shared responsibility will result in a kinder culture where students and the greater community can thrive in a positive, respectful and inclusive learning environment.
.
.
🗓The initial meeting will be held Thursday, October 24th at 6:30PM in the Jr.-Sr. High Library.
.
.
🔗More information and group goals can be found here - https://bit.ly/2nNVjPl

📢Marion is in search of individuals passionate about creating a positive, supportive and respectful learning culture for students!
.
.
In order to create an Alliance for a Kinder Culture, the school district is creating a team of faculty, staff, students, parents, administration and all other interested stakeholders to spearhead this important movement. It is our belief that coming together and accepting this challenge as a shared responsibility will result in a kinder culture where students and the greater community can thrive in a positive, respectful and inclusive learning environment.
.
.
🗓The initial meeting will be held Thursday, October 24th at 6:30PM in the Jr.-Sr. High Library.
.
.
🔗More information and group goals can be found here - https://bit.ly/2nNVjPl

post_text: While most cell phone use is frowned upon during class, one teacher at Marion is taking advantage of technology to help students track their progress throughout the year. Students in Mr. Goodell's Weight Training class are utilizing an Ap that even professional teams use for their athletes! The Ap contains a workout schedule that includes a warm up activity, shows tips on how to perform certain exercises safely and efficiently, and most importantly monitors their progress. Mr. Goodell has tailored the Ap to fit each student's fitness ability and needs, and the students enjoy using the Ap to stay on track! Just one more way #marionbelieves in engaging students to achieve their fullest potential! 💪

Help Marion CSD congratulate Coach Dick White on his induction into the Section V Boys Soccer Hall of Fame!👏
.
.
A recognition will be held during half time of the Boys Varsity Homecoming game on October 4th (approximately 7:45 PM) at the Marion Jr.-Sr. High School main soccer field. ⚽️ Former players are invited and encouraged to come!
.
.
Coach White held a 221-86-30 record over the course of 17 Seasons. He amassed 7 sectional titles, 7 county championships and 2 State Championships. Please join us as we celebrate his accomplishments!

post_text:
The first day of school is right around the corner, so to make sure that your family is ready you can start making bedtime adjustments now. Making sudden changes in sleep schedules can make it harder to learn and lead to grumpy mornings and tough starts to the school year. Letting your young scholars know that you will be starting to return to school bedtime a little at a time a couple days before you start can help avoid those "bedtime battles".

Have a great finish to your summer!
